        <div data-lang="en" style="display:none;">

          <h2>Structure of the Albanian Education System</h2>
          <p>Albania's education system is organized into four main levels: pre-school, compulsory basic education, upper secondary, and higher education. The structure was significantly reformed after Albania joined the <strong>Bologna Process in 2003</strong>, aligning it with European higher education standards.</p>

          <h3>1. Pre-school Education</h3>
          <p>Pre-school covers children aged <strong>3 to 6</strong>. It is not compulsory but widely available through state and private kindergartens.</p>

          <h3>2. Compulsory Basic Education</h3>
          <p>Basic education is <strong>compulsory for 9 years</strong> (ages 6–15):</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Lower cycle (grades 1–5):</strong> Reading, writing, mathematics and basic sciences.</li>
            <li><strong>Upper cycle (grades 6–9):</strong> Differentiated subjects by knowledge area.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>After grade 9, students sit the <strong>Basic Education State Exam</strong>.</p>

          <h3>3. Gymnasium — Upper Secondary</h3>
          <p>Gymnasium lasts <strong>3 years</strong> (grades 10–12) and is voluntary. Three types exist: General Gymnasium, Vocational School, and Arts/Sports Schools. At the end, students sit the <strong>Matura Shtetërore</strong> (State Maturity Exam).</p>

          <h2>The Albanian Grading Scale</h2>
          <p>Albania uses a <strong>numerical scale from 1 to 10</strong> at all educational levels.</p>

          <div style="background:#fff; border:1px solid #e5e7eb; border-radius:10px; overflow:hidden; margin:20px 0;">
